&gt;I do not support multi-culturalism in other words, and I &gt;think that along with political correct thinking, it is &gt;destroying the very country that I love.<br><br>
Hawaii became a state in 1959, damn near forty years ago. The population consists of Hawaiian, Japanese, Chinese, Portugese, Caucasians, Vietnamese, Cambodians, Hmong, Tai's, Hispanic, African-Americans and I am positive I have left out more than one other group of people from this list. There is no denying that we have our own set of problems over here, but, for the most part, multiculturalism seems to be working quite well, thank you very much.  I personally think I that I am an American, living in an American Culture, living the American Dream, if there is any such thing. I do not know of any here who considers themselves as anything other than an American.<br><br>
There is not a group of people that I have listed that has an agenda of &quot;destroying this very country that I love&quot;, on the other hand, I know quite a few who have contributed and sacrifice much during wartime and peacetime and, some, giving the ultimate. I know of none that do not love the United States of America and would not be one of the first  in line to do what was needed should the need arises. There seems to be no onclaves of different peoples as there is a mix geographically.<br><br>
On the other hand, I have been to New York, San Antonio, Dallas, Chicago, and even Los Angles and the impression that I have of these places are that the only thing missing are the walls of the onclaves that everyone has made for themselves.  Is this the ideal &quot;American Culture&quot; that you are touting so loudly about?  Or is it the goose-stepping neo-nazi's idea of a &quot;Aryan Culture&quot; devoid of Blacks, Brown, Yellows, or Reds?  Or how about the paranoid militia cults who think that the United Nations is out to supplant every last one of &quot;us&quot; with those heathenistic un-americans.<br><br>
Come on, Barry. Define &quot;the America that you love&quot;, because I truely do not know how the very existance of other races and their cultures or their communities can be a threat to such a thing.  The country that you love and the country that I love and the country of the mid-west farmer and the country of the Louisianna bayou shrimper all seem to be a different America, meaning different things.<br><br>
&gt;.....anti-Vietnamese feeling is part of the assimilation &gt;process and therefore a natural American reaction.<br><br>
Because fear and ignorance(your words) and idiocy and stupidity(my words) begat the anti-______ feelings of those whom immigrated to the US, thus has been a part of the assimilation process, does this make it right?  The way you phrase your words reads that this is a very good excuse for the continuation of racial bigotry and divide.<br><br>
Now, is Barry still good enough or must I go back to calling you Doc!
